Major spike clusters include:
\begin{itemize}
   \item {Dot-com bust (2000):} large negative dips and sharp positive spikes, reflecting sectoral dispersion during the crash.
   \item {Global Financial Crisis (2008--2009):} the sample’s largest negative returns (below --15\%) and the strongest rebounds (above +18\%).
   \item {COVID shock (2020):} another pair of extreme negative and positive swings.
\end{itemize}
   
\noindent Return volatility in {\autoref{fig:plot3_return_statistics}} shows the standard deviation of returns across stocks each week. Baseline dispersion is typically 3--5\% in normal periods, while spikes coincide with market crises:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Dot-com crash (peak near 15\%)
        \item Global Financial Crisis (peak around 12\%)
        \item COVID crash (peak near 13\%)
    \end{itemize}


